iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories New York - A top UN official says sexual violence is increasingly being used as "a tactic of terrorism" from Iraq, Syria and Yemen to Somalia, Nigeria and Mali.Deputy Secretary-General Amina Mohammed says "the same litany of horrors" has been told by Yazidis held captive by Islamic State extremists, girls who fled from Boko Haram, Somali women liberated from the al-Shabaab extremist group and women living under an al-Qaeda-linked group in northern Mali.She told the UN Security Council on Monday that extremist groups "are outrageously boosting profiting through the sale, trade and trafficking of women and girls."Adama Dieng, the acting UN special representative on sexual violence in conflict, said sexual violence is also "a tool of dehumanization and shame" and "a weapon of punishment and persecution."24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.